abstract = {{We study the merger histories of galaxy dark matter halos using a high-resolution ΛCDM N-body simulation. Our merger trees follow \textbackslashtextasciitilde17,000 halos with masses M0 = 1011-1013 h-1 M⊙ at z = 0 and track accretion events involving objects as small as msimeq 1010 h-1 M⊙. We find that mass assembly is remarkably self-similar in m/M0 and dominated by mergers that are \textbackslashtextasciitilde10\% of the final halo mass. While very large mergers, mgtrsim 0.4M0, are quite rare, sizeable accretion events, m \textbackslashtextasciitilde 0.1M0, are common. Over the last \textbackslashtextasciitilde10 Gyr, an overwhelming majority (\textbackslashtextasciitilde95\%) of Milky Way-sized halos with M0 = 1012 h-1 M⊙ have accreted at least one object with greater total mass than the Milky Way disk (m > 5 × 1010 h-1 M⊙), and approximately 70\% have accreted an object with more than twice that mass (m > 1011 h-1 M⊙). Our results raise serious concerns about the survival of thin-disk-dominated galaxies within the current paradigm for galaxy formation in a ΛCDM universe. In order to achieve a \textbackslashtextasciitilde70\% disk-dominated fraction in Milky Way-sized ΛCDM halos, mergers involving msimeq 2 × 1011 h-1 M⊙ objects must not destroy disks. Considering that most thick disks and bulges contain old stellar populations, the situation is even more restrictive: these mergers must not heat disks or drive gas into their centers to create young bulges.}}, 
